.SH FAUXTON
.SS Installation
.sp
Recent versions of \fI\%node.js\fP and \fI\%npm\fP are required.
.SS Get the source
.sp
Clone the CouchDB repo:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
$ git clone http://git\-wip\-us.apache.org/repos/asf/couchdb.git
$ cd couchdb
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Fauxton Setup
.sp
Install all dependencies:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
couchdb/ $ cd src/fauxton
couchdb/src/fauxton/ $ npm install
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
To avoid a npm global install add \fBnode_modules/.bin\fP to your path:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
export PATH=./node_modules/.bin:$PATH
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Or just use the wrappers in \fB\&./bin/\fP\&.
.sp
Development mode, non minified files:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
\&./bin/grunt couchdebug
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Or fully compiled install:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
\&./bin/grunt couchdb
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Dev Server
.sp
Using the dev server is the easiest way to use Fauxton, specially when
developing for it:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
grunt dev
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Deploy Fauxton
.sp
Deploy Fauxton to your local CouchDB instance:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
\&./bin/grunt couchapp_deploy
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The Fauxton be available by \fI\%/fauxton/_design/fauxton/index.html\fP
.SS Understanding Fauxton Code layout
.sp
Each bit of functionality is its own separate module or addon.
.sp
All core modules are stored under \fIapp/module\fP and any addons that are optional
are under \fIapp/addons\fP\&.
.sp
We use \fI\%backbone.js\fP and \fI\%Backbone.layoutmanager\fP quite heavily, so best to
get an idea how they work. Its best at this point to read through a couple of
the modules and addons to get an idea of how they work.
.sp
Two good starting points are \fIapp/addon/config\fP and \fIapp/modules/databases\fP\&.
.sp
Each module must have a \fIbase.js\fP file, this is read and compile when Fauxton is
deployed.
.sp
The \fIresource.js\fP file is usually for your \fBBackbone.Models\fP and
\fBBackbone.Collections\fP, \fIview.js\fP for your \fBBackbone.Views\fP\&.
.sp
The \fIroutes.js\fP is used to register a url path for your view along with what
layout, data, breadcrumbs and api point is required for the view.
.SS ToDo items
.sp
Checkout \fI\%JIRA\fP  for a list of items to do.
.SS Writing Addons
.sp
Addons allow you to extend Fauxton for a specific use case. Usually, they
have the following structure:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
+ my_addon/
| \-\-\-+ assets [optional]
|    \e \-\-\-+ less
|         \e \-\-\-\- my_addon.less
| \-\-\-+ templates/
|    \e \-\-\-\- my_addon.html \- underscore template fragments
| \-\-\-\- resources.js \- models and collections of the addon
| \-\-\-\- routes.js \- URL routing for the addon
| \-\-\-\- views.js \- views that the model provides
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Generating an Addon
.sp
We have a \fIgrunt\-init\fP template that lets you create a skeleton addon,
including all the boiler plate code. Run \fBgrunt\-init tasks/addon\fP and answer
the questions it asks to create an addon:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
± grunt\-init tasks/addon
path.existsSync is now called \(gafs.existsSync\(ga.
Running "addon" task

Please answer the following:
[?] Add on Name (WickedCool) SuperAddon
